WEBVTT

00:00:00.240 --> 00:00:01.680
Posit's own Kristin Bott.

00:00:01.680 --> 00:00:03.040
Ah, ah.

00:00:03.040 --> 00:00:04.120
Okay, fantastic.

00:00:04.120 --> 00:00:07.720
All right, folks, after all of that, good afternoon.

00:00:07.720 --> 00:00:08.640
My name is Kristin Bott,

00:00:08.640 --> 00:00:10.200
and I'm gonna close out this session

00:00:10.200 --> 00:00:13.240
and echo some of the things that you've already heard.

00:00:13.240 --> 00:00:15.720
So ears up for a little bit of repetition.

00:00:15.720 --> 00:00:19.760
So title of my talk is On Teaching Adults to Code.

00:00:19.760 --> 00:00:21.520
And I suppose I could have had

00:00:21.520 --> 00:00:23.260
a little more of a playful title here.

00:00:23.260 --> 00:00:26.840
So something like, how do you teach adults new tricks

00:00:26.840 --> 00:00:29.120
except swap out those juggling,

00:00:29.120 --> 00:00:32.560
or swap out those juggling balls for some relevant packages.

00:00:33.980 --> 00:00:36.720
So regardless of your framing,

00:00:36.720 --> 00:00:38.360
the problem that we're trying to solve here

00:00:38.360 --> 00:00:41.119
is what is a good path

00:00:41.119 --> 00:00:43.680
to reach the goal of effective education?

00:00:43.680 --> 00:00:45.360
And my guess is you could have

00:00:45.360 --> 00:00:47.060
a couple of different perspectives

00:00:47.060 --> 00:00:48.680
when you are approaching this problem.

00:00:48.680 --> 00:00:53.680
So one, you might have a team that you need to have trained.

00:00:54.240 --> 00:00:55.240
So I'm not talking about you

00:00:55.240 --> 00:00:56.419
as the person in front of the room.

00:00:57.000 --> 00:00:57.840
You're not the educator,

00:00:57.840 --> 00:01:00.099
but you have a staff that needs to gain some kind of skill,

00:01:00.099 --> 00:01:02.139
and your job is to figure out, okay,

00:01:02.139 --> 00:01:05.059
of all the training options, courses, resources,

00:01:05.059 --> 00:01:06.339
what do I do, what do I pick?

00:01:06.339 --> 00:01:08.720
How do I get my people from where they are

00:01:08.720 --> 00:01:10.639
to what they need to know?

00:01:10.639 --> 00:01:13.180
Option two, you could be that person

00:01:13.180 --> 00:01:14.139
in the front of the room.

00:01:14.139 --> 00:01:16.820
You're in that educator position,

00:01:16.820 --> 00:01:18.779
and so your job is how do I figure out

00:01:18.779 --> 00:01:20.699
how to structure and present information

00:01:20.699 --> 00:01:22.980
in a way that's going to land and stick?

00:01:22.980 --> 00:01:25.379
And then, of course, you might have something

00:01:25.379 --> 00:01:26.860
that you yourself need to learn,

00:01:26.860 --> 00:01:28.120
some skill you need to build.

00:01:28.120 --> 00:01:32.540
So all of these different perspectives on the same problem,

00:01:32.540 --> 00:01:35.699
I'm going to argue that the underlying components

00:01:35.699 --> 00:01:37.540
are going to be the same.

00:01:37.540 --> 00:01:40.440
To give you all a sense of where I'm coming from,

00:01:40.440 --> 00:01:43.099
so I've spent a lot of time thinking

00:01:43.099 --> 00:01:44.699
about how to educate effectively.

00:01:44.699 --> 00:01:47.620
Before I came to Posit, I was in higher ed for 10 years,

00:01:47.620 --> 00:01:52.620
basically at the intersection of education and technology.

00:01:52.980 --> 00:01:55.660
And for the last three and a half, almost four years,

00:01:55.660 --> 00:01:57.500
I've been with Posit Academy.

00:01:57.500 --> 00:01:58.900
For those not familiar,

00:01:58.900 --> 00:02:02.260
Academy is one of Posit's learning offerings.

00:02:02.260 --> 00:02:04.500
So we're an educational program

00:02:04.500 --> 00:02:06.459
that is built around the idea

00:02:06.459 --> 00:02:08.979
that data science is not a spectator sport.

00:02:08.979 --> 00:02:12.500
So we believe that learners need to be actively engaged

00:02:12.500 --> 00:02:15.940
with tools and concepts in order to have this stuff stick.

00:02:15.940 --> 00:02:18.259
We teach courses in foundations of data science

00:02:18.259 --> 00:02:19.899
in R and Python,

00:02:19.899 --> 00:02:22.220
a sort of intermediate programming in R course,

00:02:22.779 --> 00:02:24.820
and then an introduction to Shiny for R.

00:02:24.820 --> 00:02:27.339
We started in early 2022.

00:02:27.339 --> 00:02:30.059
We've reached more than 1,500 learners

00:02:30.059 --> 00:02:32.279
across about 100 companies.

00:02:32.279 --> 00:02:36.539
And those companies span Fortune 500, Fortune 100,

00:02:36.539 --> 00:02:38.100
top 20 pharma,

00:02:38.100 --> 00:02:41.740
public sector at the state, local, and federal level.

00:02:41.740 --> 00:02:42.820
I've got some nonprofits

00:02:42.820 --> 00:02:45.220
and different corners of the private sector.

00:02:45.220 --> 00:02:47.500
And I tell you all of that to get the point across

00:02:47.500 --> 00:02:50.000
that we've worked with a lot of different people

00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:52.179
with different backgrounds, different contexts,

00:02:53.139 --> 00:02:53.979
different skill levels, different needs,

00:02:53.979 --> 00:02:55.539
different learning styles.

00:02:55.539 --> 00:02:57.899
And I think we've been pretty effective.

00:02:57.899 --> 00:03:01.339
So I'm going to reference Academy throughout this talk,

00:03:01.339 --> 00:03:02.940
not as a product,

00:03:02.940 --> 00:03:06.139
but as an example of what a very intentionally designed

00:03:06.139 --> 00:03:07.800
educational program can look like.

00:03:07.800 --> 00:03:09.300
So I'll bring you some lessons

00:03:09.300 --> 00:03:10.440
from what we've been up to

00:03:10.440 --> 00:03:12.580
for the past more than three years.

00:03:12.580 --> 00:03:15.800
So now that I've set the stage, here we go.

00:03:15.800 --> 00:03:19.259
So this afternoon, I am going to Posit,

00:03:19.460 --> 00:03:20.300
ugh.

00:03:22.139 --> 00:03:24.419
That effective education requires three things.

00:03:24.419 --> 00:03:28.139
So thing the first, you need time over time.

00:03:28.139 --> 00:03:30.179
And I think that everyone in this room is going to nod

00:03:30.179 --> 00:03:32.460
and say, yes, yes, learning takes time, I get it.

00:03:32.460 --> 00:03:34.699
But I think it's a little more nuanced.

00:03:34.699 --> 00:03:37.059
So this is a visualization

00:03:37.059 --> 00:03:39.440
of what a one-day workshop might look like.

00:03:39.440 --> 00:03:42.100
So this is a large volume of hours

00:03:42.100 --> 00:03:45.520
over a relatively short number of days.

00:03:45.520 --> 00:03:46.360
And,

00:03:47.660 --> 00:03:48.500
okay, very good.

00:03:49.500 --> 00:03:51.619
For most people in this room,

00:03:51.619 --> 00:03:53.860
you've probably had some experience like this.

00:03:53.860 --> 00:03:55.619
It was a workshop, it was a short course,

00:03:55.619 --> 00:03:57.740
some kind of intensive training.

00:03:57.740 --> 00:04:01.380
So if that's familiar, my question for you is,

00:04:01.380 --> 00:04:04.119
how much of that did you retain?

00:04:05.259 --> 00:04:07.660
And maybe think about when you were leaving the classroom,

00:04:07.660 --> 00:04:10.539
two weeks later, two months later, four, six months later,

00:04:10.539 --> 00:04:12.820
how much of that knowledge stuck with you?

00:04:15.020 --> 00:04:17.299
I'm seeing some knowing smiles.

00:04:17.299 --> 00:04:19.140
So, oh, there's the mic, interesting.

00:04:20.779 --> 00:04:22.220
I'll just go like this.

00:04:22.220 --> 00:04:27.220
So for everyone who said, oh, not 100%,

00:04:31.059 --> 00:04:32.019
mic threw me off.

00:04:32.019 --> 00:04:34.619
For everyone who said not 100%, a couple of things.

00:04:34.619 --> 00:04:37.779
Congratulations, you are not alone.

00:04:37.779 --> 00:04:40.540
And also, that is not, you are not alone

00:04:40.540 --> 00:04:43.500
because most people forget most things that they learn

00:04:43.500 --> 00:04:45.420
in a really intense period like that.

00:04:45.420 --> 00:04:48.140
And also, that is not your fault.

00:04:48.140 --> 00:04:50.760
It is not the fault of your instructors.

00:04:50.760 --> 00:04:53.299
It's actually how our brains are made.

00:04:53.299 --> 00:04:56.320
So this is a representation of a forgetting curve,

00:04:56.320 --> 00:04:58.339
also known as an Ebbinghaus curve.

00:04:58.339 --> 00:05:00.500
He's a fellow who did the original research.

00:05:00.500 --> 00:05:04.260
The idea here is that when you initially learn something,

00:05:04.260 --> 00:05:07.019
gain a skill, your mastery is really high.

00:05:07.019 --> 00:05:09.179
And then as time goes on,

00:05:09.179 --> 00:05:11.660
your proximity to that knowledge drops

00:05:11.660 --> 00:05:15.579
and your brain simply cannot hold onto that information

00:05:15.579 --> 00:05:18.500
unless you practice.

00:05:18.500 --> 00:05:20.700
You see here that you practice once,

00:05:20.700 --> 00:05:24.019
mastery rises, and then declines over time.

00:05:24.019 --> 00:05:26.779
So if you can keep up that practice,

00:05:26.779 --> 00:05:29.320
you can help combat that forgetting.

00:05:30.239 --> 00:05:33.059
Increased practice over time, mastery stays high.

00:05:33.059 --> 00:05:35.700
This is how you have skills stick with you.

00:05:35.700 --> 00:05:38.140
So here's my same workshop experience.

00:05:38.140 --> 00:05:39.980
That is the same volume of hours

00:05:39.980 --> 00:05:42.779
spread out over a larger number of days.

00:05:42.779 --> 00:05:44.040
So if you have a choice,

00:05:44.040 --> 00:05:46.540
I would recommend trying to structure your learning

00:05:46.540 --> 00:05:49.100
more like this, a little bit bit-by-bit.

00:05:49.100 --> 00:05:51.660
Now, for everybody who was in workshops yesterday,

00:05:54.220 --> 00:05:55.100
don't despair.

00:05:55.100 --> 00:05:57.739
This is instead your nudge to go home

00:05:57.739 --> 00:05:58.859
when you're done with conf

00:05:58.859 --> 00:06:01.820
and practice those things you learned yesterday

00:06:01.820 --> 00:06:05.079
so they stick with you for six months.

00:06:06.559 --> 00:06:08.820
All right, the way that we deal with this in Academy,

00:06:08.820 --> 00:06:10.700
we teach our courses over time,

00:06:10.700 --> 00:06:13.260
so four to six weeks, depending on the topic,

00:06:13.260 --> 00:06:15.500
and we approach that content that we teach

00:06:15.500 --> 00:06:16.899
in a number of different ways,

00:06:16.899 --> 00:06:18.700
all of which are on a weekly basis.

00:06:18.700 --> 00:06:21.779
So one, you have asynchronous tutorials

00:06:21.779 --> 00:06:23.220
that you work through on your own.

00:06:23.220 --> 00:06:25.299
Those are released weekly.

00:06:25.299 --> 00:06:28.059
We center our courses around data science projects.

00:06:28.059 --> 00:06:32.579
So little bits of that project is made available every week,

00:06:32.579 --> 00:06:34.660
and we put our learners in small groups.

00:06:34.660 --> 00:06:36.980
Those groups convene also on a weekly basis

00:06:36.980 --> 00:06:38.940
so you can learn together.

00:06:38.940 --> 00:06:41.559
So time over time, your take-home here

00:06:41.559 --> 00:06:44.279
is whenever possible, spread out your learning.

00:06:45.500 --> 00:06:46.940
Now, the end of that last section

00:06:46.940 --> 00:06:48.859
maybe sounds familiar to anyone

00:06:48.859 --> 00:06:51.279
who has ever learned a musical instrument,

00:06:51.279 --> 00:06:54.739
that idea that you need to practice a little bit every day.

00:06:54.739 --> 00:06:59.059
So practice, yes, but I don't think that practice is enough.

00:06:59.059 --> 00:07:00.820
So quick audience survey.

00:07:02.579 --> 00:07:03.700
How many people have worked

00:07:03.700 --> 00:07:05.420
with the Palmer Penguins package?

00:07:05.420 --> 00:07:07.540
We've already seen them once today.

00:07:07.540 --> 00:07:09.579
All right, fantastic, thank you.

00:07:09.579 --> 00:07:13.459
Now, how many people in this room study penguins?

00:07:15.700 --> 00:07:17.260
Antarctic biologists?

00:07:18.220 --> 00:07:19.579
Any ornithologists?

00:07:19.579 --> 00:07:20.420
Maybe.

00:07:20.420 --> 00:07:22.579
All right, we've got a, thank you, thank you, bird people.

00:07:22.579 --> 00:07:23.420
Good to see you.

00:07:25.500 --> 00:07:28.100
So Palmer Penguins is a fantastic dataset.

00:07:28.100 --> 00:07:31.140
It's a classic because it is accessible.

00:07:31.140 --> 00:07:32.299
There are things that you can do

00:07:32.299 --> 00:07:34.820
in terms of basic exploratory data analysis, graphs.

00:07:35.220 --> 00:07:38.380
There's some nice diversity of data types in there.

00:07:38.380 --> 00:07:40.140
So it's really good for beginners.

00:07:40.140 --> 00:07:41.739
You get to learn things about penguins.

00:07:41.739 --> 00:07:42.660
Penguins are neat.

00:07:42.660 --> 00:07:44.899
My background's in ecology.

00:07:44.899 --> 00:07:49.100
But my guess is that for most of the people in this room,

00:07:49.100 --> 00:07:52.779
two exceptions, there's some distance

00:07:52.779 --> 00:07:55.140
between what you need to do with data

00:07:55.140 --> 00:07:57.380
when you have those data skills

00:07:57.380 --> 00:07:59.540
and what you were doing with the penguin data.

00:07:59.540 --> 00:08:02.100
So whether that's coming from a background of bench science,

00:08:02.100 --> 00:08:03.579
somewhere in the healthcare industry,

00:08:03.579 --> 00:08:05.700
maybe you do finance analytics,

00:08:05.700 --> 00:08:07.940
there's a distance you have to travel

00:08:07.940 --> 00:08:12.100
from that practice in penguins

00:08:12.100 --> 00:08:13.899
to whatever you're actually doing.

00:08:13.899 --> 00:08:15.820
And wouldn't it be neat if we can somehow shrink that?

00:08:15.820 --> 00:08:18.019
So the way that we approach this in Academy,

00:08:18.019 --> 00:08:19.220
those data science projects

00:08:19.220 --> 00:08:21.859
that are the core of our courses,

00:08:21.859 --> 00:08:24.540
we offer those in a variety of different topics

00:08:24.540 --> 00:08:25.540
so that you can have something,

00:08:25.540 --> 00:08:27.779
hopefully, that's a little bit closer to what you're doing.

00:08:27.779 --> 00:08:29.940
So you might be in epidemiology.

00:08:29.940 --> 00:08:31.220
You might work on measles.

00:08:31.220 --> 00:08:32.460
We don't have a measles project,

00:08:32.460 --> 00:08:33.739
but we have a COVID project.

00:08:33.739 --> 00:08:36.419
And so we can keep you sort of in the same neighborhood

00:08:36.419 --> 00:08:37.859
of what you're used to thinking about

00:08:37.859 --> 00:08:39.859
what's going to be useful for you eventually,

00:08:39.859 --> 00:08:43.539
a little bit closer than, say, while delightful, penguins.

00:08:44.780 --> 00:08:49.179
All right, so you sort of got a spoiler for this idea

00:08:49.179 --> 00:08:51.260
from both earlier mentions of scaffolding

00:08:51.260 --> 00:08:52.859
and Ryan's laddering idea.

00:08:52.859 --> 00:08:56.299
But here we have a learner in the lower portion of the slide

00:08:56.299 --> 00:08:58.739
and they would like to practice their purr skills.

00:08:58.739 --> 00:09:02.099
They just have to get from where they are to purr.

00:09:02.580 --> 00:09:07.580
All right, so practice, yes, relevance when you can get it,

00:09:09.859 --> 00:09:12.739
and that practice needs to be within reach.

00:09:12.739 --> 00:09:14.419
So what I mean by that,

00:09:14.419 --> 00:09:17.059
and this calls back to Ryan's concept of laddering,

00:09:17.059 --> 00:09:20.659
what you need to do is present information

00:09:20.659 --> 00:09:24.820
in incremental ways, increase challenge slowly over time

00:09:24.820 --> 00:09:29.380
so that distance is possible for learners to cover

00:09:29.380 --> 00:09:31.219
so they can get from where they are

00:09:31.219 --> 00:09:32.940
to where they need to be.

00:09:32.940 --> 00:09:35.380
To get a sense of what this looks like in practice,

00:09:35.380 --> 00:09:37.179
notice penguins, good data set,

00:09:37.179 --> 00:09:38.900
we use it in our foundational stuff.

00:09:38.900 --> 00:09:40.859
So this is the first time that people see Summarize

00:09:40.859 --> 00:09:42.659
in one of our courses.

00:09:42.659 --> 00:09:45.460
There's a bunch of code, you run it.

00:09:45.460 --> 00:09:48.179
So introduction, you get to just sort of take that in,

00:09:48.179 --> 00:09:50.219
that's your cognitive work.

00:09:50.219 --> 00:09:51.500
Later on in the course,

00:09:51.500 --> 00:09:54.419
that code becomes more and more skeletal

00:09:54.419 --> 00:09:56.820
so you need to do more and more work, more thinking,

00:09:56.820 --> 00:09:58.299
you engage a little bit extra,

00:09:58.299 --> 00:10:00.260
and then by the end, we turn to you

00:10:00.260 --> 00:10:02.659
and effectively in a conversational sentence say,

00:10:02.659 --> 00:10:05.780
hey, do a thing with the data please, thank you,

00:10:05.780 --> 00:10:07.500
and you respond in code.

00:10:09.260 --> 00:10:10.780
In terms of the projects,

00:10:10.780 --> 00:10:14.299
we might turn to you and say,

00:10:14.299 --> 00:10:16.700
okay, here is a data set,

00:10:16.700 --> 00:10:20.140
here is a visual I have made with that data set,

00:10:20.140 --> 00:10:23.219
your turn, go back and recreate that thing.

00:10:23.219 --> 00:10:25.299
So there's still structure there,

00:10:25.299 --> 00:10:29.979
but it is more open-ended than the lessons,

00:10:30.739 --> 00:10:31.580
but more structured than just saying,

00:10:31.580 --> 00:10:33.859
oh, go and do something, whatever you want.

00:10:35.219 --> 00:10:37.299
Once you've done that recreation portion,

00:10:37.299 --> 00:10:39.900
you can then build on that and do something

00:10:39.900 --> 00:10:41.780
with the data that feels more relevant for you

00:10:41.780 --> 00:10:43.580
and where you need to go.

00:10:43.580 --> 00:10:47.859
Okay, so practice relevant within reach or take home here,

00:10:47.859 --> 00:10:50.460
keep that practice close to the final application

00:10:50.460 --> 00:10:53.619
and provide small steps to help learners get to their goals.

00:10:54.539 --> 00:10:56.500
All right, let's try this out.

00:10:56.500 --> 00:10:58.299
So here we have a learner

00:10:58.340 --> 00:11:01.619
and this learner has relevant tasks,

00:11:01.619 --> 00:11:04.659
relevant data and time set aside.

00:11:04.659 --> 00:11:05.900
All right, let's do this.

00:11:05.900 --> 00:11:09.700
So we are coding, we are coding, everything is great,

00:11:09.700 --> 00:11:12.179
this is a ton of fun.

00:11:12.179 --> 00:11:17.179
I just got an error and I got another error

00:11:17.500 --> 00:11:19.099
and now nothing is working

00:11:19.979 --> 00:11:22.340
and I don't like this and everything is bad.

00:11:22.340 --> 00:11:27.340
All right, so what can we do to avoid this kind of explosion,

00:11:32.460 --> 00:11:36.900
existential crisis or failure to learn?

00:11:39.260 --> 00:11:43.900
What happens if we give this learner some friends?

00:11:45.619 --> 00:11:48.659
So I think the, and I see Alyssa over there.

00:11:48.659 --> 00:11:53.659
So I think the last component of effective education

00:11:54.020 --> 00:11:56.580
is a community of practice.

00:11:56.580 --> 00:11:58.820
So again, we've heard about this throughout the talks

00:11:58.820 --> 00:12:00.700
for the rest of this session.

00:12:00.700 --> 00:12:03.380
Community is very important for humans.

00:12:03.380 --> 00:12:07.179
We are social creatures, we do not do well in isolation

00:12:07.179 --> 00:12:09.460
and I think education is no exception

00:12:09.460 --> 00:12:11.460
to that guiding principle.

00:12:11.460 --> 00:12:13.099
And what I'd like to do in this section

00:12:13.099 --> 00:12:16.099
is tuck nearly immediately into what we do in Academy

00:12:16.099 --> 00:12:19.739
because there's lots of different ways to build community

00:12:19.739 --> 00:12:21.900
and my hope is that if I give you examples

00:12:21.900 --> 00:12:24.619
from what we've done, you can maybe apply some of that

00:12:24.619 --> 00:12:26.140
to your different corner and get something

00:12:26.140 --> 00:12:28.140
really useful out of this talk.

00:12:28.140 --> 00:12:31.380
So for starters, we take our learners

00:12:31.380 --> 00:12:34.460
and put them into small groups, say eight to 10 people.

00:12:34.460 --> 00:12:35.619
So you get to know each other,

00:12:35.619 --> 00:12:37.340
you start building a little bit of connection

00:12:37.340 --> 00:12:40.140
to foster some of that psychological safety.

00:12:40.140 --> 00:12:44.460
We have those groups facilitated by experienced mentors.

00:12:44.460 --> 00:12:47.380
So these are people who bring experience in both code

00:12:47.380 --> 00:12:51.020
but also education and that means that they can come in

00:12:51.020 --> 00:12:53.739
and yes, they can demonstrate tips and tricks

00:12:53.739 --> 00:12:56.580
and best practices and how to find information,

00:12:56.580 --> 00:12:59.739
the kinds of things that are easier to learn in real time

00:12:59.739 --> 00:13:02.419
from a human as opposed to in a tutorial.

00:13:03.659 --> 00:13:07.020
And while all of that is useful and good,

00:13:07.020 --> 00:13:10.020
I would argue that's not the most important part

00:13:10.020 --> 00:13:12.299
of having the mentor in the room.

00:13:12.340 --> 00:13:15.900
The mentor can build the kind of environment

00:13:15.900 --> 00:13:18.700
where effective learning can really happen.

00:13:18.700 --> 00:13:22.580
So psychological safety across the learners, sure.

00:13:22.580 --> 00:13:24.260
But the mentor's in a position to do things

00:13:24.260 --> 00:13:28.260
like normalize not knowing, normalize asking questions,

00:13:28.260 --> 00:13:32.619
normalize making mistakes and be able to navigate

00:13:32.619 --> 00:13:34.099
those moments of struggle.

00:13:34.099 --> 00:13:36.820
You have someone to turn to who will say,

00:13:36.820 --> 00:13:39.140
oh, does this feel hard?

00:13:39.140 --> 00:13:41.580
If this feels hard, that's correct.

00:13:41.580 --> 00:13:43.299
You are having a normal reaction.

00:13:43.299 --> 00:13:44.780
You're doing something that is hard.

00:13:44.780 --> 00:13:48.659
You are learning a new language and also you can do this.

00:13:48.659 --> 00:13:50.179
We can get through this together.

00:13:50.179 --> 00:13:51.739
Come on, let's figure this out.

00:13:52.739 --> 00:13:56.419
Part of what I do in Academy is I run our mentor program

00:13:56.419 --> 00:13:59.659
and so I meet with all of our active mentors every week.

00:13:59.659 --> 00:14:02.260
So they stay super close to those groups

00:14:02.260 --> 00:14:03.820
and how things are going,

00:14:03.820 --> 00:14:06.380
which means I get to talk to our great mentors every week.

00:14:06.380 --> 00:14:09.900
Here's a line from one of those meetings.

00:14:09.940 --> 00:14:14.219
It often surprises me how much reassurance

00:14:14.219 --> 00:14:16.979
adults need when they're learning.

00:14:16.979 --> 00:14:19.900
And I call out adults as a particular learning population

00:14:19.900 --> 00:14:21.580
because these folks are different

00:14:21.580 --> 00:14:24.780
from Kelly's room full of college students.

00:14:24.780 --> 00:14:27.700
So our learners are working professionals

00:14:27.700 --> 00:14:30.219
and like probably everyone in this room,

00:14:30.219 --> 00:14:34.059
they're very used to being very good at what they do.

00:14:34.059 --> 00:14:37.219
And so it can be incredibly destabilizing

00:14:37.260 --> 00:14:40.619
to have moments of, I don't know what's going on.

00:14:40.619 --> 00:14:42.179
I don't know what this code is doing.

00:14:42.179 --> 00:14:44.859
I don't know why this code doesn't work.

00:14:44.859 --> 00:14:46.059
I need help.

00:14:47.500 --> 00:14:49.179
And with a learner in the room,

00:14:49.179 --> 00:14:52.739
you have someone who can model the kind of kindness

00:14:52.739 --> 00:14:56.340
and curiosity that helps build a place

00:14:56.340 --> 00:14:58.059
where people feel comfortable

00:14:58.059 --> 00:15:00.059
doing the vulnerable business of learning,

00:15:00.059 --> 00:15:04.260
where people are excited to solve problems together,

00:15:04.260 --> 00:15:06.539
to celebrate together.

00:15:06.539 --> 00:15:07.619
And if you want to think about this

00:15:07.619 --> 00:15:11.940
from more of an organizational level, strategic angle,

00:15:11.940 --> 00:15:13.900
communities of practice also help

00:15:13.900 --> 00:15:16.260
make your group more resilient.

00:15:16.260 --> 00:15:20.140
So you can have staff leave, retire, change jobs.

00:15:20.140 --> 00:15:21.820
You can bring new people in

00:15:21.820 --> 00:15:25.059
because what you've done is create a matrix of people

00:15:25.059 --> 00:15:27.140
who are connected to each other.

00:15:27.140 --> 00:15:30.299
So changes are going to be easier within that group.

00:15:32.099 --> 00:15:36.219
And I said that I would make this tangible and actionable.

00:15:37.219 --> 00:15:39.700
What you're looking at is a mashup

00:15:39.700 --> 00:15:42.260
of a couple of the bingo cards

00:15:42.260 --> 00:15:43.539
we put together for our Mentos.

00:15:43.539 --> 00:15:45.260
So these are meant to be top-of-mind,

00:15:45.260 --> 00:15:47.659
maybe top-of-desk resources,

00:15:47.659 --> 00:15:50.099
just little things to keep in mind

00:15:50.099 --> 00:15:51.739
while you are working with people.

00:15:51.739 --> 00:15:54.140
So little, small, actionable bits.

00:15:54.140 --> 00:15:55.580
And I'll pause here for a second

00:15:55.580 --> 00:15:57.460
because there's a lot of text to read.

00:16:02.900 --> 00:16:05.340
And in the interest of time, I'm going to scoot on.

00:16:05.340 --> 00:16:08.059
I've got a link to the slides at the end.

00:16:08.059 --> 00:16:10.020
So community of practice.

00:16:10.020 --> 00:16:11.780
So your action here is to seek out

00:16:11.780 --> 00:16:14.500
and foster connection for review.

00:16:14.500 --> 00:16:17.460
Our big three are time over time,

00:16:17.460 --> 00:16:19.539
relevant practice that is within reach,

00:16:19.539 --> 00:16:22.820
and all of this happens within a community of practice.

00:16:22.820 --> 00:16:27.820
And in closing, I want to come back to that last point.

00:16:28.380 --> 00:16:31.859
So learning in community can be really fun and rewarding.

00:16:31.859 --> 00:16:34.380
Again, we've heard about this throughout the session.

00:16:34.380 --> 00:16:36.219
You have someone to turn to for that moment of,

00:16:36.219 --> 00:16:37.979
ha-ha, I did it.

00:16:37.979 --> 00:16:39.940
And you have someone who can help you

00:16:39.940 --> 00:16:43.020
in the ugly moments of, ugh, I got stuck.

00:16:43.020 --> 00:16:46.780
You also get to watch someone else experience the joy

00:16:46.780 --> 00:16:50.140
of doing something they didn't think was possible for them.

00:16:51.140 --> 00:16:53.820
But if you zoom out a little bit,

00:16:53.820 --> 00:16:58.820
we are much stronger together than we are as individuals.

00:16:59.219 --> 00:17:02.640
And so when you work in a community like this,

00:17:02.640 --> 00:17:07.400
you are working to get the meaningful work done together,

00:17:07.400 --> 00:17:10.800
which is maybe the most important part of all of this.

00:17:10.800 --> 00:17:12.680
So that's what I've got.

00:17:12.680 --> 00:17:14.119
I'll take any questions if I have time.

00:17:14.119 --> 00:17:15.099
Thank you.

00:17:15.099 --> 00:17:16.719
Thank you.

00:17:16.719 --> 00:17:17.560
Thank you.

00:17:17.560 --> 00:17:18.400
Thank you.

00:17:18.400 --> 00:17:19.219
Thank you.

00:17:19.219 --> 00:17:20.060
Thank you.

00:17:20.060 --> 00:17:20.900
Thank you.

00:17:20.900 --> 00:17:21.880
Thank you.

00:17:21.880 --> 00:17:23.479
Okay, let's do one question.

00:17:23.479 --> 00:17:25.439
What's the balance between teaching the community

00:17:25.439 --> 00:17:28.699
something useful versus something they're interested in?

00:17:29.699 --> 00:17:32.540
Oh, so useful,

00:17:32.540 --> 00:17:35.739
so something useful versus something they're excited about.

00:17:35.739 --> 00:17:37.859
I would be curious who's making both of those

00:17:37.859 --> 00:17:41.699
determinations, but feminism aside.

00:17:43.140 --> 00:17:44.339
Some laughing.

00:17:44.339 --> 00:17:47.739
I think what I would do is try to figure out

00:17:47.739 --> 00:17:49.939
what overlap between those two things could look like.

00:17:49.939 --> 00:17:52.979
So what, like, where's the excitement

00:17:52.979 --> 00:17:54.979
and is there a way to sort of dovetail that

00:17:54.979 --> 00:17:56.380
into whatever application

00:17:56.380 --> 00:17:58.280
we're driving towards that's required?

00:17:59.380 --> 00:18:00.219
Sounds great to me.

00:18:00.219 --> 00:18:01.739
Okay, fantastic.

00:18:01.739 --> 00:18:03.880
All right, let's thank all these speakers.

00:18:03.880 --> 00:18:05.380
Awesome.

00:18:05.380 --> 00:18:07.119
Thank you, everyone.

